    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-08-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-08-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="527"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d527">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">310.2/8–2054</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the United Nations Adviser, Bureau of Far
                        Eastern Affairs</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BACONRE1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bacon</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">to the Regional Planning Adviser, Bureau of Far
                        Eastern Affairs</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ogburn</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-08-20">August 20,
                            1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <item>Subject:</item>
                    <item>Chinese Representation</item>
                </list>
                <p>The Secretary informed the Belgian Ambassador yesterday that we would like very
                    much to support Belgium for a Security Council post.<note n="1" xml:id="d527fn1"
                        >For the text of the memorandum of conversation, see <ref target="#pg_580"
                            >p. 580</ref>.</note> Indicating that there was no sense of trade
                    involved, the Secretary expressed the hope that the Belgians would continue to
                    support our position on Chinese representation. The Belgian Ambassador, without
                    giving any commitment, made assuring remarks to the general effect that Belgium
                    had taken a prominent part in the finding of aggression against the Chinese
                    Communists and that this and other matters would have to be cleared up, of
                    course, before consideration could be given to seating the Chinese Communists in
                    the United Nations.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
